### Version

Yosys 0.59+44 (git sha1 ba99c0590, g++ 15.2.1 -march=x86-64 -mtune=generic -O2 -fno-plt -fexceptions -fstack-clash-protection -fcf-protection -fno-omit-frame-pointer -mno-omit-leaf-frame-pointer -fPIC -O3)

### On which OS did this happen?

Linux

### Reproduction Steps

```sv
module inout_task_bug (
    input logic clk,
    input logic in_bus,
    output logic bus_reg_out,
    output logic out_bus
);
    logic bus_reg;

    assign bus_reg_out = bus_reg;

    task automatic toggle(inout logic bus);
        bus = ~bus;
    endtask

    always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
        bus_reg <= in_bus;
        toggle(bus_reg);
        out_bus <= bus_reg;
    end

    //always_comb assert(!$isunknown(bus_reg_out));
    //always_comb assert(!$isunknown(out_bus));    
endmodule
EOT

hierarchy -top inout_task_bug
proc_prune
write_verilog -sv -noattr output.sv

chformal -lower
select inout_task_bug

sat -enable_undef -set-init-undef -set-def clk -prove-asserts -verify -seq 5 -prove-skip 1 -show bus_reg_out,out_bus,in_bus
```

The bug seems to be in `proc_prune`
I am sorry i did not manage to write asserts to prove that even without the `proc_prune` the outputs were not undefined. I also tried to prove that in_bus was connected to something to no avail. But I suppose any member of the yosys headquarters will know exactly how to write this. 



### Expected Behavior

Initially I thought the bug was a scheduling semantics one so I analysed it as follows. 
Nevertheless when trying to write the yosys test script I saw that the problem might be a simpler `proc_prune` bug (that might be linked with semantics as this piece of code tries to trigger such border cases). I left the analysis in case it proves itself relevant to the bug. 

According to IEEE 1800-2023 Section 4.9.7:
> "Subroutine argument passing is by value, and it copies in on invocation and copies out on return. The copy-out-on-the-return function behaves in the same manner as does any blocking assignment."

So from what I understand here we have:

- Active region: `always_ff` executes
  - `bus_reg <= in_bus;` -> schedules NBA for `bus_reg = in_bus` in NBA region
  - `toggle(bus_reg);` -> Executes immediately:
    - Copy-in: reads current `bus_reg` value
    - Modifies: `bus = ~bus`
    - Copy-out: writes back to `bus_reg` (blocking assignment in Active region)
  - `out_bus <= bus_reg;` -> schedules NBA for `out_bus = (modified bus_reg)` in NBA region
- NBA region
  - `bus_reg` gets the value from `in_bus` (overwriting the task modification)
  - `out_bus` gets the inverted original `bus_reg` value
`bus_reg <= in_bus` is in the NBA region

In any case we should not be having `x` values everywhere. 

### Actual Behavior

The produced verilog file is : 

with `proc_prune`
```sv
module inout_task_bug(clk, in_bus, bus_reg_out, out_bus);
  input clk;
  wire clk;
  input in_bus;
  wire in_bus;
  output bus_reg_out;
  wire bus_reg_out;
  output out_bus;
  reg out_bus;
  wire _0_;
  wire _1_;
  wire _2_;
  wire _3_;
  reg bus_reg;
  reg \toggle$func$<<EOT:17$1.bus ;
  assign _3_ = ~ bus_reg;
  always_comb begin
  end
  always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
      out_bus <= _1_;
      bus_reg <= _0_;
      \toggle$func$<<EOT:17$1.bus  <= 1'hx;
  end
  assign bus_reg_out = bus_reg;
  assign _1_ = _3_;
  assign _0_ = _3_;
  assign _2_ = _3_;
endmodule
```

We can see here that `in_bus` is not connected to anything so all the output values become `x`.

Thanks for the work on yosys, sorry for the incomplete script.
PS : I checked for bugs with proc_prune but did not see any that seemed to be duplicates.

